      <h2>How to Choose the Best Game Engine</h2>
      <p>Choosing the right game engine is one of the most important decisions you'll make when starting your game development journey. As a beginner, it's easy to get caught up in finding the "most powerful" engine, but often the best engine is the one that gets out of your way and allows you to actually finish your game.</p>

      <h3>Consider Your Goals</h3>
      <p>If your dream is to create a simple 2D platformer or RPG, jumping straight into <strong>Unreal Engine</strong> might be a mistake. The steep learning curve and massive toolkit can be overwhelming. Instead, engines like <strong>Godot</strong> or <strong>GameMaker</strong> are purpose-built for 2D and will allow you to prototype your ideas much faster.</p>

      <h2>The Learning Curve vs. Career Prospects</h2>
      <p>There is often a tradeoff between how easy an engine is to learn and how well it prepares you for a career in the AAA gaming industry.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Unity and Unreal Engine:</strong> These are the industry standards. Learning C# (Unity) or C++ (Unreal) is highly transferable, and knowledge of these engines makes you highly employable at professional studios.</li>
        <li><strong>Godot and GameMaker:</strong> While fantastic for indie developers and solo projects, they are less commonly used in large-scale professional studios. However, the foundational concepts of game design you learn (game loops, physics, collisions) are universal.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Pricing and Royalties</h3>
      <p>For beginners, pricing shouldn't be a major barrier. All of the engines listed offer generous free tiers. <strong>Godot</strong> stands out as being 100% free and open-source forever, meaning you never owe royalties. <strong>Unity</strong> and <strong>Unreal Engine</strong> are free until you hit significant revenue milestones ($100k and $1M respectively), which is a fantastic deal for solo developers just starting out.</p>
